The day I took the March Bon Appetit from my mailbox and saw this on the cover, I couldn't wait to make it. Finally, last night I made it, and it was fantastic! I was a bit skeptical with the mixed reviews. I cut the recipe in half, and made it in 4 gratin dishes. Also made the filling in the morning. My only changes were reducing the olive oil, using 1% milk, and Percorino Romano, as I looked everywhere for kasseri, and couldn't find it. So, so delicious. Time consuming, but well worth it.

Rating: 3
Taking a few suggestions here really helped as I shortened the cook time by using ground lamb and I used less liquid, which resulted in a thick meaty-eggplant mixture that wouldn't be soupy underneath the mash. I used fire-roasted crushed tomatoes, so I wasn't able to cut back on that liquid, so it had to be the beef stock. Instead I threw in a bouillion cube to supplement. All in all, with the can of tomatoes, I used only 2 c of broth. Also, because I used ground lamb, I was able to use less olive oil too and I added about a tablespoon of flour after the onions were cooked to help thicken, as I did not "dust" the lamb cubes and brown. This worked very well, as it made a roux. I did use kasseri cheese. You shouldn't substitute feta, but pecorino romano as the recipe suggests, as kasseri is very similar and not as salty as feta. Plus the kasseri is harder and can be grated. One other little change, which might be personal taste, was to rough chop the eggplant after it was cooked. I thought that texture would work better with my ground lamb. I gave this three stars because it was better than good but not exceptional.

