Rating: 4
Humm I must have seen this recipe before somewhere else because I have it, and have made it with some exceptions. I'm always on the look out for anything that has lamb or eggplant. And was hoping this would be a huge deviation but alas its the same one. When I compared the recipes I did indeed find that there was a difference between the ratio of solids to liquid. With there being more liquid then is necessary in this recipe. I also have found this to be the case with several of the recipes. In the case of this one, just off hand I can see that the liquid ratio would be affected by the canned tomatoes. Depending on the brand the liquid ratio would vary dramatically. Higher end tomatoes have 1/4 cup of liquid and the lower end can have almost a cup. Needless to say that would change the viscosity and cooking time greatly. I have found that when these recipes are tested they use the best of the best so if you dont have then you will need to adjust. In a standard market the meats for instance is low grade choice where as they will use prime or the upper grades for all of their meats. You would have to make adjustments the meats are not the same. I do agree that to change the recipe beyond what it should be (adding velvetta as a substitute for any cheese or making a dish that is oven based in a microwave, OK that is just wrong, but I have seen people posting reviews that have done this). Perhaps other's have the time and money to expend on a recipe that they can see without a few tweeks would end in disaster and do it anyway for the "experience" and then just toss the messy results. But in these economic times I don't see many people doing that. Not to mention that I am Jewish so cant do the meat and milk thing. So in this recipe there is not butter in the potatoes.

